The Miller-Rabin primality test is a more advanced method for determining whether a number is prime. The test works by repeatedly testing whether the number is a witness to the compositeness of the number in question. If no witness is found after a certain number of iterations, then the number is considered prime. Here is an example of how to implement this method in Python:
